{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600121"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:01:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:01:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15609"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15609"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.14,0.1,0.57,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66734"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8300"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52187"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3879"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5115"},{"type":"tags","id":"7005"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"8221"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20034"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22303"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66734"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA histological section from a thyroid nodule shows sheets and nests of polygonal cells with granular cytoplasm (Image). There is abundant pink-staining amorphous material between the cell nests. Immunohistochemistry is positive for calcitonin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anaplastic carcinoma","Follicular adenoma","Follicular carcinoma","Medullary carcinoma","Papillary carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological features described are classic for \u003Cstrong\u003Emedullary carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the thyroid. The amorphous pink material represents amyloid deposits, which are characteristic of this tumour type. These tumours arise from parafollicular C cells (not follicular cells) and produce calcitonin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaplastic carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows marked cellular pleomorphism and widespread necrosis. \u003Cstrong\u003EFollicular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Efollicular adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E both show follicular differentiation with colloid-containing follicles. \u003Cstrong\u003EPapillary carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows characteristic papillary architecture with nuclear features including ground glass nuclei and nuclear grooves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medullary thyroid carcinoma arises from parafollicular C cells and shows characteristic amyloid deposits between nests of tumour cells","Medullary thyroid carcinoma produces calcitonin and can be part of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2 syndrome"],"references":["\u0022Medullary thyroid carcinoma - high mag\u0022 by Nephron is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Medullary_thyroid_carcinoma_-_high_mag.jpg","Shah JP. Thyroid carcinoma: epidemiology, histology, and diagnosis. Clin Adv Hematol Oncol. 2015 Apr;13(4 Suppl 4):3-6. PMID: 26430868; PMCID: PMC5526593","Kitahara CM, Schneider AB. Epidemiology of Thyroid Cancer. Cancer Epidemiol Biomarkers Prev. 2022 Jul 1;31(7):1284-1297. doi: 10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-21-1440. PMID: 35775227; PMCID: PMC9473679","Boucai L, Zafereo M, Cabanillas ME. Thyroid Cancer: A Review. JAMA. 2024 Feb 6;331(5):425-435. doi: 10.1001/jama.2023.26348. PMID: 38319329","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52187"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15609"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21175"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21175"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vIcS7mshhyd5cEhsZ3yEiwyoHiy5qg.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vIcS7mshhyd5cEhsZ3yEiwyoHiy5qg.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1000}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52187"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T20:37:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T20:38:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8300"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66734"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":